That fixes the problem, but we lost the feature, to display variable with the
same name in static methods.

It's because a class object will always answer java.lang.Class as it's type, not
the type of the object.

A test case:

public class Bug_44195 {
  static int i= 42;
  public static void main(String[] args) {
    new Bug_44195_2().bar();
    Bug_44195_2.foo();
  }
}
class Bug_44195_2 extends Bug_44195 {
  static int i= 64;
  public static void foo() {
    System.out.println("test"); //  <-- breakpoint here
  }
  public void bar() {
    System.out.println("test"); //  <-- breakpoint here
  }
}

When the first breakpoint is hit, the variables are displayed with the declaring
type in parenthesis.
When the second breakpoint is hit, the extra information about the declaring
type are no more displayed.
